Why Jerome Powell has to go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – thus to possibly the most powerful position in the world economy?
A wrong decision here can have grave consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system adequately, thereby paving the way for the worst worldwide economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' reaction to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and nurtured a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There is a multitude of clichés why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be confirmed in his position.
It would be a demonstration of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
We need someone with experience to lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
I have heard exactly the same arguments 25 years ago when I was chair of the economic advisory board to US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were sufficient to convince Clinton, and the country paid a heavy price for its decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little heed to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and refused him a second term after Volcker had brought inflation under control.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he aimed for deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation in comparison to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets will be efficient, stable, fair, and competitive on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the USA have always held clearly articulated, but distinctly different views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populist delusions).
From my perspective, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, marginalized groups are only brought into the macroeconomy during tight labor markets, and wage disparities are reduced.
The coming years will likely be a test for any US Federal Reserve chairman.
The United States is already facing difficult decisions regarding what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate among African Americans, who have yet to regain their pre-pandemic levels?
Would interest rate hikes (and thereby an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While mispricing with mortgage-backed securities secured by collateralized debt played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of even stronger and more pervasive mispricing associated with climate change and the valuation of assets.
What should the Fed do regarding this?
Powell is not the man for the job.
Initially, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby endangered the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, while other central bankers worldwide have already identified this as the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not fall under the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never encountered a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
A glaring lack of competition and insufficient regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
Yet every second-year student would have known that monetary policy should not be tightened and interest rates raised during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
In contrast: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade was characterized by a series of misjudgments that extend back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many observers of the Fed insist that inequality is not the bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as early hikes in interest rates can stifle growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock trades by top Fed officials has undermined trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long worried me.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed official should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock trades would appear improper.
The Fed is similar in some respects to the US Supreme Court.
This is supposed to stand above politics, yet since Bush v. Gore we know that is not the case.
Trump has made it clear to all those who still had doubts.
Even the Fed is allegedly supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan, by following their party's deregulation agenda, clearly showed that this is not the case either.
Yet while the Federal Reserve Board makes crucial decisions affecting all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates in the hands of the Fed chairman – much more so than with the Supreme Court chief justice.
It is the Fed chairman who decides what comes up for a vote and which topics are deferred or prioritized.
The climate question is just an example where it is crucial who sits at the helm.
The US needs a central bank that commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitively determined financial sector.
Who believes that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far, lacks insight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-leaning lawyer like Powell.
Someone is needed who possesses deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly many people who fulfill these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone who has already proven his abilities.
Lael Brainard already sits on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her competence and earned market confidence – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a chairwoman who ensures continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who also shares his economic and social program.
